  "prompt": "What is the best open-source captive portal for a WiFi Hospot?",
  "response": "Selecting the best open-source captive portal for a WiFi hotspot depends on various factors such as your specific needs, technical expertise, and scalability requirements. Here are some popular open-source options that are widely regarded as effective:\n\n1. **CoovaChilli**:\n   - CoovaChilli is a feature-rich and widely used open-source captive portal.\n   - It provides robust authentication methods, including integration with RADIUS servers.\n   - It is highly customizable and supports various network configurations.\n   - Suitable for environments requiring flexibility and scalability.\n\n2. **pfSense Captive Portal**:\n   - pfSense is an open-source firewall and router platform that includes a captive portal feature.\n   - User-friendly web interface for configuration.\n   - Supports RADIUS authentication and can integrate with various external authentication servers.\n   - Ideal for users who need both firewall and captive portal functionalities.\n\n3. **PacketFence**:\n   - PacketFence offers advanced network access control capabilities alongside its captive portal.\n   - Includes features like intrusion detection, BYOD support, and seamless integration with various network devices.\n   - Comprehensive documentation and active community support.\n   - Suitable for larger and more complex network environments.\n\n4. **Nodogsplash**:\n   - Nodogsplash is a lightweight and simple captive portal solution.\n   - Easy to set up and configure, making it ideal for small to medium-sized deployments.\n   - Provides basic network access control without the need for RADIUS servers.\n   - Good choice for straightforward captive portal requirements.\n\n5. **Chillispot**:\n   - Chillispot, while older, is a reliable captive portal solution that integrates well with RADIUS authentication.\n   - Known for its simplicity and effectiveness in small to medium-sized environments.\n   - Offers necessary features for basic captive portal functionality.\n\nUltimately, the best choice will depend on your specific requirements, technical expertise, and the complexity of your network infrastructure. Consider factors such as ease of use, support for authentication methods, scalability, and community support when making your decision.",
